text.tspan: Simulation based inference in the Human Neocortical Neurosolver software reveals a calcium-mediated
decoupling between spiking and field activity underlying macroscale M/EEG event related potentials
Nicholas Tolley1,2, Pedro L. C. Rogrigues3, Alexandre Gramfort3, Stephanie R. Jones1,2
1Brown University Neuroscience Graduate Program, 2Carney Institute for Brain Science, Providence, RI, 3Université Paris-Saclay Inria-CEA, Palaiseau, France

flowRoot.flowPara: Current dipole event related potentials (ERP) primarily reflect intracellular current flow in apical dendrites of cortical pyramidal neurons
We have applied the Human Neocortical Neurosolver (HNN) neural modeling framework.
The Human Neocortical Neurosolver (HNN) is a neural modeling framework designed for cell and circuit level interpretation of MEG/EEG5.
SBI in HNN quantifies the ERP-spike decoupling
Characterizing bidirectional decoupling with multi-modal observations
This research was supported by National Science Foundation Grant 1935749, and the National Institute of Health Grants 1DP2NS111817-01, U24EB029005, and RO1EB022889
Simulation based inference (SBI) enables the application of Bayesian inference to models with intractable likelihoods like HNN7,8
Posterior distributions were conditioned on ERP waveforms, cell-specific firing rates, or a combination of the two
ERPs and associated spiking can exhibit a bidirectional decoupling
The combinattion of multi-modal neural data enables more precise parameter predictions
